// I Ching moving-line texts (Sage voice). Generated from iching-oracle-384-lines.md.
// LINE_DATA[kingWenNumber] = [line1(bottom) ... line6(top)]; 384 lines total.
window.LINE_DATA = {
"1": [
"The dragon lies hidden in the deep. The hour has not come; do not rise.",
"The dragon shows itself in the field. Seek out the one who can see you.",
"Strong all day and watchful at night, you walk the edge of danger and take no harm.",
"You hover at the brink, free to leap or to wait. Either choice is clean.",
"The dragon flies in the open sky. Your strength has found its hour; let it be seen.",
"Flown too high, the dragon finds only thin air and regret. Pride has carried you past your height."
],
"2": [
"Frost underfoot in the morning. The hard ice it promises is already on its way; read the small sign.",
"Straight, level, and wide, you act without contriving, and nothing is left unserved.",
"Keep your brilliance hidden and your work quiet; serve the task to its finish and claim none of the credit.",
"Tie the sack shut. Say nothing, show nothing, and neither praise nor blame can reach you.",
"Yellow at the center, modest in the lower place, you hold the quiet ground from which great fortune grows.",
"When the yielding forgets itself and fights for mastery, both sides bleed into the ground."
],
"3": [
"The first push meets a wall. Hold your ground and gather helpers before you move.",
"The cart stalls and the horses pull apart; what looks like a thief is one who comes in good faith. Wait, and the union keeps its proper hour.",
"To chase the deer into the forest without a guide is only to lose yourself among the trees. Let it go.",
"The horses have halted; reach for the hand that is offered and go to meet it. The union you seek will bless you.",
"Your giving is held back before it can spread. In small things hold firm; force the great ones now and you stumble.",
"Horse and cart stand parted, and the tears that fall are blood. When nothing will move, do not break yourself trying."
],
"4": [
"The young fool learns first by the firm rule that frees him; loosen it too soon and he wanders into shame.",
"Bear with the inexperienced in kindness and they ripen; the one who can hold many gently is fit to hold the house.",
"Do not throw yourself away on the first dazzling thing that passes; the one who loses all self-command gains nothing.",
"Folly tangled in its own daydreams brings only humiliation; come back to the ground and ask to be taught.",
"The open, childlike not-knowing that wants to learn draws good fortune to it.",
"Correct the folly only enough to stop the harm; punishment that becomes its own cruelty is itself a wrong."
],
"5": [
"Wait out in the open meadow, far from the danger, and keep to your ordinary days. There is no fault in this.",
"Wait now on the sand, nearer the edge; a little gossip drifts your way, but hold steady and it ends well.",
"Wait in the mud at the water's brink and you draw trouble toward you; you have come too close before the time.",
"You wait now in blood, in the pit itself. Keep still, keep your head, and let yourself be lifted clear.",
"Wait at the set table, fed and rested, in the calm at the center of it; hold here and good fortune comes.",
"You have fallen into the pit, and three you did not invite arrive; meet them with honor and the end is good."
],
"6": [
"Do not drag the quarrel out; bear a little gossip now and let it drop, and the end is good.",
"You cannot win this contest, so do not wage it; turn home and yield, and no harm reaches those behind you.",
"Live on what you have honestly earned, hold quietly to it through the danger, and seek no glory; the end comes out well.",
"Since the fight cannot be won, turn back from it, make peace with how things stand, and rest in what is right.",
"Bring the dispute before one who is fair and strong, and let true judgment settle it; this turns out well for you.",
"A prize wrung from open war is held only a moment; what is won by force is torn away again and again."
],
"7": [
"An army moves only in good order; set the discipline first, for a force loosed without it brings disaster.",
"Stand in the midst of your people, sharing what they bear, and the trust you earn there is worth more than any decoration.",
"When command is divided and the unfit carry the burden, the wagons come home loaded with the dead. Let one will lead.",
"There is no shame in falling back when the ground is wrong; an orderly retreat keeps the strength for a better field.",
"Strike only the quarry that has come into your field; name the threat plainly, set the seasoned one in command, and the rest follow without ruin.",
"When the work is won, reward each according to their worth, and keep the small and grasping out of the seats of power."
],
"8": [
"Come together in plain sincerity; let your heart be full as a brimming bowl and the good fortune overflows on its own.",
"Let the bond form from within, freely given rather than chased; held in truth, it brings good fortune.",
"You are binding yourself to the wrong people; loyalty poured into what is hollow only costs you.",
"Hold openly to the one worth holding to, even beyond your circle; given without reserve, the union prospers.",
"Lead by leaving the door open: take those who freely come, let the unwilling go, and force no one. This is union without fear.",
"To join a thing that has no true center is to join nothing; without a head to hold it, the binding fails."
],
"9": [
"Turn back to your own true way the moment you feel yourself stray; returning so easily, how could you be at fault?",
"Let yourself be drawn back into good company rather than pushing on alone; there is fortune in the return.",
"Force the matter and the wheel-spokes fly loose; man and wife glare past each other. Strength wasted in friction goes nowhere.",
"Hold to sincerity and the fear bleeds away; truth spoken from the heart calms even those above you.",
"Be sincere and bound in good faith, and your strength becomes shared wealth; you are richer for your neighbor.",
"The rain has fallen and a fragile rest has come; the small power has done its work, so press no further now or you spoil it."
],
"10": [
"Walk plainly, wanting nothing extra, and you go forward without fault.",
"Tread a smooth and level course, quiet and self-contained; the one who keeps to the solitary even way fares well.",
"Half-blind and limping, you take on what your strength cannot match; step on the tiger so and it turns and bites. Know what you actually can do.",
"You stand on the tiger's tail; move with held breath and watchful care, and you come through it to good fortune.",
"Walk with resolve, deciding cleanly, but never forget the danger you are walking through.",
"Look back over how you have carried yourself; when the whole of your conduct rings true, the highest good fortune follows."
],
"11": [
"Pull one good stalk and the others come up with it, root and kin together; gather the worthy and the whole undertaking thrives.",
"Bear with the rough, cross the hard water boldly, forget no one however distant, and play no favorites; this is how you walk the steady middle.",
"Every level field meets a slope, every going turns toward return; hold firm through the coming dip and enjoy the good that is still in your hands.",
"Come down freely to those below, making nothing of your wealth, meeting your neighbors open-handed and sincere.",
"Let the high give itself to the low in good faith, as a noble house weds its daughter outward; such union brings the highest blessing.",
"The wall is crumbling back into the moat; the good season is ending, so muster no armies, set only your own house in order, and meet the turn quietly."
],
"12": [
"Pull one stalk and its roots and kin rise too; in a stopped time, withdraw together with your own and hold firm, and it goes well.",
"The small endure by bending and flattering; let them. Your task is to bear the stagnation whole, and it becomes the making of you.",
"Those who schemed in the stopped time carry their shame inwardly; let that quiet disgrace turn you back toward what is honest.",
"When the turn begins, act only at the call of what is highest in you; move so, and those of like heart share the blessing.",
"The standstill is breaking; meet the relief without trusting it blindly, and bind what you build to deep roots, asking always what might still fail.",
"The blockage falls away at last; first the long stillness, then the good fortune it was holding back for you."
],
"13": [
"Meet others openly at the gate, in the daylight where all can see; bonds begun without secrecy carry no fault.",
"When fellowship shrinks to your own narrow clan, shutting others out, it turns small and brings humiliation.",
"Mistrust arms itself in the thicket and watches from the hilltop; held in suspicion like this, you cannot move for years.",
"You have climbed your wall ready to strike, then see the attack is wrong and come down; in that turning back lies good fortune.",
"Those truly bound weep at being kept apart, then laugh when at last they meet; the deep union is worth the hard struggle to reach it.",
"Fellowship out in the open meadow, plain and undemanding; it asks little and leaves no regret."
],
"14": [
"Keep clear of what would harm you, stay mindful of the danger in plenty, and your abundance stays clean of fault.",
"You have a great wagon to carry the load; your means are equal to the work, so set out and undertake it.",
"Lay your abundance open in service of something higher than yourself; the small and grasping could never do this.",
"Hold yourself apart from the swollen and the showy; refusing to flaunt what you have keeps you without fault.",
"Be truthful and approachable, yet keep your dignity; warmth that still commands respect brings good fortune.",
"Carry your fullness humbly and in service, and you are blessed from above; nothing here fails to further you."
],
"15": [
"Modest and unassuming, you can cross even the great water; the one who claims little is carried far.",
"Modesty that has sunk so deep it shows of itself, without trying; hold to it and good fortune follows.",
"Do real work and stay low about it; the one who has earned much and boasts none of it carries everything through.",
"In all you set in motion, lean toward the modest; there is nothing that this does not help.",
"Make no show of your wealth before your neighbor; when you must act firmly, even then let no arrogance enter it.",
"Turn the modesty inward first and discipline your own house; correct yourself before you move to correct anything outside."
],
"16": [
"Enthusiasm that trumpets its own connections rings hollow and draws misfortune; the noise gives you away.",
"Firm as a rock, you read the turn before the day is out and do not wait on the mood of the crowd; this clear timing brings good fortune.",
"Enthusiasm that only stares upward, waiting on another's favor, breeds regret; so does dithering once the moment is plain.",
"Be the true source from which the gladness springs, and great things come of it; trust it, and friends gather to you as hair gathers to the clasp.",
"Pressed and ailing under a constant weight, you do not die of it; the very pressure keeps you from sinking into easy ruin.",
"Enthusiasm gone blind to itself runs to waste; yet wake from the delusion even now, and you take no lasting harm."
],
"17": [
"When the standard shifts, move with it; open your door and meet many kinds of people, and your acts bear fruit.",
"Cling to the small and easy company and you lose the strong companion worth having; you cannot hold both.",
"Choose the worthy bond and let the lesser one go; in giving up the smaller you find what you were truly seeking.",
"Following may bring you a crowd and a kind of success; if you grip it for your own sake it sours, so walk in sincerity and stay clear.",
"Set your heart on following what is genuinely good, and the good fortune is sure.",
"Bind yourself wholly to the highest, and you are bound in turn and led to the heights; devotion this complete is honored."
],
"18": [
"Mend what those before you let spoil; take it up with care and a little fear, and what was failing turns out well in your hands.",
"Repair the gentler kind of decay with a gentle hand; do not bear down too hard, or you bruise what you mean to heal.",
"Go at the old rot a touch too vigorously and you will feel some regret, yet better that than leaving it; the fault stays small.",
"Merely tolerating the spoilage, letting it slide on, leads only to slow humiliation; tolerance here is its own decay.",
"Set the inherited wrong right with steady skill and a clean heart, and you meet with well-earned praise.",
"Step back from the contest of position and serve a higher aim; some are called to mend the world without seeking its rank."
],
"19": [
"Draw near in good company and right spirit; the approach made together, held firm, brings good fortune.",
"Advance with others toward the good, glad and unafraid of the turn to come; everything furthers the one who approaches so.",
"An easy, careless drawing-near that takes the welcome for granted helps nothing; feel the unease honestly and you set it right.",
"Approach all the way, openly and without holding back; meeting fully like this, you are free of fault.",
"Draw near with wisdom, the way the great delegate to the able and trust them; this clarity brings good fortune.",
"Approach with a large and generous heart, asking nothing for yourself; such greatness of spirit brings good fortune and no blame."
],
"20": [
"Seeing only the surface, like a child who looks and understands nothing; forgivable in the simple, but in one who should know better it is a falling short.",
"Peering out through the crack of the door, you catch only a sliver and call it the whole; widen your view before you judge.",
"Look honestly at the shape of your own life, and let what you see there decide whether to advance or to wait.",
"See the light at the very heart of things, and let yourself be drawn close to it to serve; from there your influence does real good.",
"Examine your own life with a clear and unflinching eye; the one who can truly look at himself comes through without fault.",
"Look on your life from above, as one freed of his own small stake in it; seen from that height, you are without blame."
],
"21": [
"A first small wrong, checked early; the foot is set in the stocks before it can walk further into harm, and no real blame remains.",
"Bite through the soft offense so cleanly you sink in to the nose; firmness against a yielding wrong sets it right without fault.",
"You bite into something old and tainted and taste the poison of it; expect a little humiliation, but you are not in the wrong to try.",
"Gnawing through tough, gristled resistance, you find the metal at its core; stay hard, stay mindful of the danger, and fortune is yours.",
"Hard, dried resistance gives at last and yields its gold; hold firm and alert to the risk, and you come through clean.",
"Deaf to every warning, the wrong is repeated until the cangue locks around the neck; correction refused this long ends in disaster."
],
"22": [
"Grace your own feet and walk rather than ride; refuse the borrowed splendor of the carriage and go on plainly by your own steps.",
"Adornment that merely follows the chin it grows on; let your beauty serve the substance beneath it and never lead.",
"Lustrous and at ease in your grace, hold steadily to what is real beneath the shine, and good fortune keeps with you.",
"At the crossroads of ornament and plainness you choose the plain, and what is true comes to you on white wings; what seemed a raider is a suitor, come at the right time.",
"Drawn to the simple grace of hills and gardens, your gift of silk looks poor and small; bear the brief embarrassment, for the modest choice ends well.",
"Grace stripped back to pure white simplicity, ornament fallen away; nothing is left but the true form, and there is no fault in it."
],
"23": [
"The decay begins at the very legs of the bed; those who try to stand firm on a base already rotting are pulled down with it.",
"The splitting climbs to the frame of the bed; still no support left, and holding your old ground here only ruins you. Yield the position.",
"Break with the failing thing yourself, step away from the crowd sliding down; in that clean parting there is no blame.",
"The split reaches the skin now, the danger gone past the structure to the flesh; this is the worst of it, so take no risks and simply survive it.",
"Order returns: like fish falling into rank, the many align around what is worthy; led gracefully, all of it now furthers.",
"One great fruit hangs uneaten, the seed of the whole next season; the worthy is carried up and renewed while the hollow loses even its roof."
],
"24": [
"You have strayed only a little; turn back now, while the distance is short, and there is nothing to regret and much to gain.",
"A calm, willing return, helped by good company you are glad to rejoin; coming back so quietly brings good fortune.",
"You drift off and catch yourself, again and again; there is danger in the wavering, yet each honest return keeps you free of blame.",
"Walking among many who go the wrong way, you turn back alone toward what is right; the lonely return is the true one.",
"Return wholeheartedly, owning the turn without excuse; such noble honesty leaves no room for regret.",
"Miss the moment of return entirely, harden against the turn, and ruin gathers from within and without; the road back closes for a long season."
],
"25": [
"Act from your clean first impulse, free of calculation, and that innocence carries you to good fortune.",
"Do the work for its own sake, not counting the harvest while you plow; freed of grasping at the result, you may safely undertake much.",
"Sometimes misfortune lands on you through no fault of yours, the way one man's strayed cow is another's loss; take the undeserved blow without reading guilt into it.",
"Hold quietly to what is truly yours and stay constant; keeping faith with your own nature, you remain free of fault.",
"When trouble comes that you did not cause, do not thrash at it with remedies; left alone, it passes of itself.",
"Even innocent action goes wrong when it moves against the hour; when the time forbids it, the right act done now brings misfortune, so do not force it."
],
"26": [
"Danger stands close; the strength in you strains to move, but this is the hour to hold it back and wait.",
"Take the axle from the wagon and stop yourself willingly; the force is real, but checking it now is the wiser strength.",
"Now the way opens and your power may run, like a good horse joining the others; stay sharp to the danger, keep your skills honed daily, and press on toward your aim.",
"Curb the wild force while it is young, as a board guards the horns of a calf before they can gore; tamed early, it brings great good fortune.",
"Master the danger at its root, the way gelding takes the fury from the boar without a fight; the strength is rendered safe, and fortune follows.",
"The long restraint is fulfilled and the great force is loosed in step with heaven itself; held this well, it crosses every barrier and succeeds."
],
"27": [
"You let go your own inner riches and sit envying what others eat; turning from the spring within you to covet outside is the root of misfortune.",
"Begging your nourishment from those above and below, going against your nature to be fed, leaves you forever wanting; keep on so and it ends badly.",
"Chasing the wrong nourishment, the kind that never fills, brings ruin; turn from it wholly and do not return to it for a long, long while.",
"Reach upward for what truly feeds you and share it on with hungry eyes for the worthy; seeking high nourishment to give it away again is without fault.",
"Knowing you cannot feed others by your own strength alone, lean on the wise and stay where you are; hold firm here and do not attempt the great crossing yet.",
"You have become the source from which others are fed; carry that weight mindful of its danger, and so steadied you may cross even the great water."
],
"28": [
"Before bearing a great weight, lay it down on soft white rushes; extra care under a heavy thing is never wasted, and keeps you free of fault.",
"The old poplar sends fresh shoots from its root, the old man takes a young wife; an unlikely renewal stirs, and it furthers everything.",
"The ridgepole bends to the snapping point and you push on stubbornly; refusing all help under so great a load, you bring the break on yourself.",
"The sagging beam is propped and holds; brace the weak point and good fortune comes, but lean on others for your own hidden ends and it shames you.",
"The withered tree manages a few late blossoms, the old woman a young husband; a brief flowering that cannot last, neither shameful nor much to praise.",
"Sometimes the only way through is into water that closes over your head; wade in knowing the cost, and though there is loss, there is no blame in the daring."
],
"29": [
"Numb to the danger, you sink from one pit into a deeper one; falling so carelessly into the depths is misfortune.",
"The danger is real all around you; do not reach for the great escape now, only for the small, sure handhold within your grasp.",
"Abyss before you and abyss behind, every way steep; at a moment like this, hold still and wait, for any thrashing only drops you deeper.",
"In the worst strait, share what little is real and plain, a jug of wine and a bowl of rice passed through the window; honest simplicity between people carries you through, and there is no blame.",
"The water rises only to the brim and then flows on, never overfilling; do no more than the danger asks, fill the hollow and move, and you stay clear of fault.",
"Lost in the depths so long you are bound as if in a thorn-walled prison, and for years find no opening; when you have strayed this far from the way, the suffering must run its course."
],
"30": [
"At the day's first steps your tracks run every which way in confusion; gather yourself toward what matters with serious heart, and there is no fault.",
"Light held at the balanced center, golden and clear, clinging to nothing extreme; this measured radiance brings the highest good fortune.",
"In the light of the setting sun some drum and sing while others wail at the coming dark; cling to either the giddy or the grieving extreme and you fall into misfortune.",
"A flame that bursts up all at once, blazes wild, burns out, and is cast aside; brilliance with no steadiness flares and is gone.",
"Caught between fierce powers you weep in floods and lament aloud, and that very anguish, honestly felt, turns the tide toward good fortune.",
"When you must act against a wrong, strike only the ringleader of it and spare those merely swept along; punish the root, not every leaf, and you stay without blame."
],
"31": [
"The first faint stirring reaches only your big toe; the attraction has barely begun, too slight yet to move you, so let it ripen.",
"The pull reaches your calves and they twitch to run ahead; rushing toward it now goes wrong, while staying quietly put brings good fortune.",
"The urge grips your thighs and they move only where the body leads; following every impulse this slavishly is beneath you and brings humiliation.",
"Keep your heart steady and true and the regret dissolves; let it dart restlessly after this one and that, and only the few you truly fix on will answer.",
"The influence settles in the back of the neck, firm and beyond the reach of mood; moved at a depth too steady to waver, you carry no regret.",
"Influence that lives only in the jaws and tongue is mere talk; words alone, with nothing felt beneath them, sway no one for long."
],
"32": [
"Demanding deep constancy all at once, before the roots have grown, brings lasting misfortune; nothing is helped by forcing what only time can make durable.",
"Hold steadily to the middle within your strength, and the regret you carried simply dissolves.",
"Give your character no constancy, let your moods rule you, and disgrace follows you about; the one who will not stay himself is shamed again and again.",
"Hunting long and faithfully in the wrong field, you catch nothing; constancy aimed at what cannot yield it is loyalty wasted.",
"Hold one course faithfully come what may; this gentle steadfastness blesses the one who follows, but for the one who must lead and adapt, rigid sameness goes wrong.",
"Restlessness made into a way of life, forever stirred up and never settled, brings misfortune; duration cannot grow in soil that is always churning."
],
"33": [
"Caught at the very tail of the withdrawal, you are in danger of being overtaken; do not start anything new now, simply hold still and wait it out.",
"Bind yourself to what is right with the grip of tough yellow leather, a will so fixed that nothing can tear you loose from your purpose.",
"A retreat held back by clinging entanglements frays the nerves; you cannot leave cleanly, so keep close only those who are truly yours and make the best of it.",
"Let go and withdraw of your own free will; the strong release what they must and rise by it, while the grasping cling and are dragged down.",
"Retreat in good time and good spirit, without bitterness toward what you leave; this friendly, clear-eyed withdrawal, held firm, brings good fortune.",
"Step away lightly, even gladly, with nothing left to snag you; a retreat this free and untroubled turns everything to your good."
],
"34": [
"Strength gathered only in the toes, all eager push at the lowest point; charge ahead on so shallow a footing and you come to grief.",
"The power is real and the way is open; hold to the steady middle, neither forcing nor flinching, and good fortune is yours.",
"The small use their strength to bully and ram; do not, for that road is dangerous, like the goat that butts the hedge and only tangles its own horns.",
"Persist quietly and the regret falls away; the hedge gives, the horns come free, and your strength rolls forward sure as the axle of a great cart.",
"Let the stubborn force go as easily as a goat slips loose, dropping the fight without a pang; released so lightly, you carry no regret.",
"Lowered head jammed in the hedge, the goat can move neither back nor forward; when blind force has trapped you, see the bind clearly and that honesty itself begins to free you."
],
"35": [
"You move forward and are turned back at the gate; hold steady and stay calm, and meeting no welcome yet does you no harm, for the good fortune is still coming.",
"You advance, but with a heavy heart and little encouragement; keep faith, and the blessing reaches you as if handed down from those who came before.",
"Those around you come into accord and rise with you; carried up by shared trust, your lingering regret dissolves.",
"Pushing ahead by grasping and hoarding, scurrying like a hoarding rodent; advance won this greedily, however firmly held, is full of danger.",
"Let the regret go and stop weighing every gain and loss; move forward free of that anxious reckoning, and your undertakings prosper.",
"Pressing forward with lowered horns is fit only for disciplining your own house, never for conquest; do it knowing the danger and it turns out well, but pushed past that it brings shame."
],
"36": [
"The light goes down even as you fly, so you fold your wings and go hungry rather than betray yourself; hold to your aim through the lean days though others mutter.",
"The darkness wounds you in the thigh, hindering but not stopping you; lend your remaining strength like a strong horse to rescue what can be saved, and good fortune follows.",
"In the thick of it you happen on the very source of the darkness and could strike it down; do not rush to set everything right at once, for deep wrongs heal slowly.",
"You see straight into the heart of the corruption from within, and knowing it fully, you quietly leave through the gate before it can claim you.",
"Forced to live close to the darkness, keep your inner light hidden as the wise have always done under cruel rule; veiled constancy is what serves you now.",
"The darkness overreaches and undoes itself; having climbed as high as heaven, it plunges all the way to the depths, and its own excess ends it."
],
"37": [
"Set firm, clear bounds within the household from the start; with order kept early, the regret never has room to arise.",
"Do not follow every passing whim; tend faithfully to the nourishing center of things, the daily care that holds a house, and good fortune follows.",
"When tempers flare, firm correction brings some regret yet keeps the house sound; let things slide into giddy indulgence instead and it ends in humiliation. Better too strict than too slack.",
"Enrich the household from within, the quiet keeper who makes the whole place thrive; in this lies great good fortune.",
"Come to your family as a true sovereign comes, ruling by love rather than fear; lead the close circle so and there is nothing to dread.",
"Let your authority rest on real and respected work, on what you are rather than what you demand; held this way, it brings good fortune in the end."
],
"38": [
"When estrangement sets in, let the regret pass; do not chase the horse that has bolted, for it returns of itself, and simply guard against missteps with those who mean you ill.",
"You meet the one you need by chance, in a cramped side street rather than any hall of state; take the unplanned meeting as it comes, for there is no fault in it.",
"At first everything balks, the cart hauled back and you affronted and hurt; a wretched start, but hold on, for it comes right in the end.",
"Cut off and alone in the midst of discord, you find one kindred soul to trust in good faith; even amid the danger, that honest meeting clears the blame.",
"Let the regret dissolve; the ally you misjudged cuts straight through to reach you, so go to meet him without hesitation, for how could that be a mistake?",
"So warped by mistrust you see a friend as a mud-caked beast and a cart of demons, you draw the bow, then lower it as the truth dawns; the stranger you feared is kin, and as the misunderstanding breaks like rain, good fortune comes."
],
"39": [
"Push forward into the barrier and you only meet more of it; turn back instead, and the coming-home earns you praise.",
"Obstacle heaps on obstacle through no fault of your own, because the duty you serve is larger than yourself; meet the hardship as service, not as failure.",
"The way ahead is blocked, so you turn back toward those who depend on you; coming home now is the strength, not the going on.",
"Going forward alone only piles up obstruction; come back and join with others, and what you could not do alone becomes possible together.",
"In the very thick of the worst blockage, when you hold your ground without flinching, friends gather to you from every side.",
"Going on serves nothing now; turn back, and the return brings great good fortune, especially toward the one whose wisdom can guide you through."
],
"40": [
"The strain has just broken and the way is open; rest quietly in the relief and do nothing more, and there is no fault.",
"Clear out the sly, foxlike influences from your field and recover your straight, honest center; hold to that uprightness and good fortune follows.",
"Carrying the burdens of a laborer yet flaunting the comforts of a lord, you invite thieves to your door; such a mismatched show, kept up, ends in humiliation.",
"Free yourself from the wrong attachment clinging to you like a snared toe, and once you are loose the true companion comes, the one you can trust.",
"Deliver yourself, above all, from your own faults; when the worthy visibly frees himself, the wavering see he means it and fall away from wrong.",
"Take clear and final aim at the entrenched obstacle perched high out of reach, and bring it down with one decisive stroke; this furthers everything."
],
"41": [
"When your own task is done, go quickly to help another and take no credit; but weigh it carefully, so that lifting them does not drain them.",
"Hold to your own worth and do not throw yourself away to please; you serve others best by staying whole, not by emptying yourself for them.",
"Three walking together is one too many and the crowd thins to a true pair; the one who walks alone finds the companion meant for him. What is overfull is pared to its right number.",
"Lessen your own faults, and lessen them in earnest; as the burden of them falls away, others hurry gladly toward you, and no blame remains.",
"When you have given honestly, blessing returns past all expectation, more than the richest gift could buy and not to be turned aside; this is the highest good fortune.",
"Increase that flows to you without taking from anyone is clean gain; hold to it and prosper, undertake much, and find your good bound up now with the many rather than with yourself alone."
],
"42": [
"The current is pouring toward you, so put it to great use; backed by such fullness, undertake the large and worthy thing, and it crowns you with good fortune.",
"Blessing comes to you from beyond all opposing, more than any fortune-teller's shells could turn aside; hold steady and true, and what is given lifts you to the highest place.",
"Even hard, unwelcome events can enrich you; if your heart is sincere and you keep to the middle, you take no blame, and you carry the matter openly to those who must know.",
"Keep to the middle way and counsel those above you faithfully, and they will follow; trusted so, you become the one called on to steady great changes.",
"If your heart is truly kind, you need not ask whether it is seen; goodness given without bargaining brings the highest fortune, and is known for what it is.",
"He gives to no one and grasps at all, and now the blows fall on him; a heart this unsteady, fixed on getting and never on giving, draws misfortune to itself."
],
"43": [
"All the force is in your forward toes, eager to charge before you are ready; rush in unequal to the task and the very strength becomes your stumble.",
"Sound the alarm honestly and stay armed and watchful through the night; prepared for the danger, you have nothing to fear from it.",
"Wearing your resolve hard in your face invites misfortune; hold the inner resolve quietly instead, even if it means walking alone through the rain, soaked and grumbled at, for there is no real fault in it.",
"Worn raw and pushing forward against the grain, you make it harder than it is; let yourself be led gently for once, and the regret would lift, though stubbornness will likely refuse to hear it.",
"Even the weeds close to home must be rooted out with steady resolve; do it firmly but keep to the balanced middle, and you stay free of blame.",
"Thinking the danger past, you let down your guard and raise no warning cry; that final, premature ease is just where the misfortune comes in."
],
"44": [
"Check the small intrusion at once, with a firm bronze brake; halt it now and it stays good, but let it run free and even this lean, harmless-looking thing rages out of all control.",
"Keep the small dark force quietly contained, like a fish kept in the tank under your eye; held in check it does no harm, but do not let it out among others.",
"Held back yet still tempted, you chafe and move with difficulty; stay keenly aware of the danger and you avoid any serious mistake.",
"Lose your grip on the small force entirely, let the fish slip the tank, and the harm spreads beyond recall; estrangement from what you should have held brings misfortune.",
"Shelter your real strength quietly, like ripe fruit shaded under leaves, making no display; hold your worth hidden and in time what is yours drops to you as if from heaven.",
"You hold others off stiffly, horns lowered, too proud to meet anyone; the stiffness brings you a little humiliation, but since it keeps you clear of the wrong, there is no real blame."
],
"45": [
"Your sincerity wavers, so the group keeps scattering and re-forming in confusion; call out honestly to the one who steadies you, and after a single clasp of hands the trouble turns to laughter.",
"Let yourself be drawn into the gathering rather than forcing your way in; come willingly, and even a small, sincere offering is enough to bring good fortune.",
"You hover at the edge of the circle, sighing to belong, finding no opening; go toward it anyway, swallow the slight awkwardness, and joining is still better than standing apart.",
"Gather others selflessly, for the good of the whole and not your own advancement; working so unselfishly brings great good fortune and no blame.",
"Hold the center by right and your gathering takes no blame; for the ones not yet won over, do not force them, but be so constant and true that in time their distrust dissolves.",
"Left outside, longing to belong and moved to tears that no one yet receives, you grieve openly; there is no fault in the longing, and felt honestly it opens the door."
],
"46": [
"Rise from the very bottom welcomed and trusted, drawn upward by those above who believe in you; this confident first ascent brings great good fortune.",
"Plain and sincere, you need no lavish display; a small honest offering opens the way upward, and there is no fault in coming with so little.",
"The way opens so freely it is like walking up into a city with no walls and no resistance; advance, but stay watchful, for ease this complete deserves a steady eye.",
"You are welcomed at the height and given an honored place, received as a guest is received on the sacred mountain; good fortune, and no blame.",
"Climb by sure, deliberate steps, gaining one solid foothold before the next; hold to that patient steadiness and the ascent brings good fortune.",
"Pushing on blindly upward in the dark, no longer seeing where you climb; here the only safety is unbroken, watchful constancy, so keep your footing and do not lunge."
],
"47": [
"Worn down and sunk into a gloomy hollow beneath a bare tree, you lose all sight of the way for a long, dark while; do not let the low mood become your whole world.",
"Hemmed in even amid plenty, restless at the full table, help is quietly on its way; stay where you are, turn to what is sacred, and do not set out yet, and you keep clear of blame.",
"You lean on what cuts you and butt against what will not move, then come home to find no comfort even there; oppression you bring on yourself by grasping at thorns ends in misery.",
"Help comes slowly, hindered by your own comfortable position as if stuck in a golden carriage; the delay is a little shaming, but stay faithful and you arrive in the end.",
"Cut off above and below, oppressed even by those who should aid you, you bear it with dignity, and relief steals in gently; turn to the sacred and quiet gladness returns.",
"Tangled in clinging vines, you waver, telling yourself any move will be regretted; feel that hesitation as the real trap, resolve to move, and the very first step turns it to good fortune."
],
"48": [
"You settle for the muddy bottom, the stale water no creature will touch; sink to the silt of yourself and you give the world nothing to drink, and it turns away.",
"The water is there, yet you fritter it on small aims, shooting at minnows while the jug cracks and leaks; gifts left unused and uncared for simply drain away.",
"The well is cleaned and clear and still no one drinks; what a grief, that so much good in you goes unoffered. Let yourself be drawn on, and the good is shared by all.",
"Take time to line the well and make its walls sound; turning inward to repair your own foundations is no idleness, and it leaves you without fault.",
"Deep down the spring runs clear and cold, fit to drink at last; your true source is open now, so let others come and be refreshed by it.",
"The water is drawn freely and never fails, dependable for all who come; a source given without stint or hindrance is the highest good fortune there is."
],
"49": [
"The hour for change has not yet ripened; bind yourself fast, as if wrapped in tough yellow hide, and hold still rather than move too soon.",
"When the right day has truly come, then make the change; acting at last in the ripe moment brings good fortune and leaves no blame.",
"Lunge into upheaval too eagerly and it ends badly, yet clinging stubbornly to the old is dangerous too; let the need for change be weighed and confirmed again and again, and then people will trust the move.",
"Now the regret falls away and others believe in you; remake what is genuinely outworn, and the deep change brings good fortune.",
"The great renewer transforms boldly and clearly, his new pattern as vivid as a tiger's stripes; so plainly right is the change that people trust it before any proof is asked.",
"The worthy make the deep inner change, while the lesser merely repaint their faces; do not keep forcing more upheaval now, but hold steady in the new order, and good fortune follows."
],
"50": [
"Tip the cauldron over to empty out the old stale dregs; clearing away what has gone rotten, even by a humble means, opens the vessel for good new use and leaves no blame.",
"The vessel is full of real nourishment, and though others eye it with envy, they cannot touch it; keep clear of their grasping and the good fortune is yours.",
"The handle is changed and for a while you cannot serve what you hold, the good food going to waste; stay patient through the blockage, and when the cooling rain comes the regret is spent and it ends well.",
"Trusted with more than you can carry, the legs give way and the whole meal is spilled and fouls you; taking on a duty past your strength, you bring the disgrace on yourself.",
"The vessel is fitted with fine handles and golden rings, open and ready to be lifted and shared; stay humble and true in this readiness, and it furthers you.",
"Handled now with rings of jade, strong and gentle in perfect measure; carried so, the work of nourishing the world brings the greatest good fortune, and nothing fails to further."
],
"51": [
"The shock strikes and you cry out, then steady and laugh; meet the jolt fully, let it pass through you, and the fright gives way to good fortune.",
"The shock comes hard and you lose what you valued and must flee to high ground; do not chase after what is swept away, for in its own time, when the danger settles, it returns to you.",
"The shock leaves you rattled and at a loss; let the very fright move you to right action, and you come through it without misfortune.",
"The shock falls into mud and dies there, swallowed up; weighed down and stuck, you let the rousing energy sink, and nothing wakes in you.",
"Shock after shock buffets you from every side, full of danger, yet nothing essential is truly lost; keep your center, attend to what genuinely must be done, and you hold.",
"When the shock comes you stare about in terror and your nerve fails; rush forward now and you stumble, but heed the warning while it still strikes your neighbor and not yet you, and ready yourself, and you take no harm though others gossip."
],
"52": [
"Be still at the very first step, before you have set off; halt while halting is easy, and there is no fault in it, only quiet strength.",
"You stop your own legs but are still carried along by the one ahead of you, unable to free him or yourself; held in that half-stillness, the heart goes unsatisfied.",
"Forcing yourself rigidly still, clamping down on the very hinge of your movement; stillness made by force is dangerous, and the heart smothers under it.",
"Bring your whole self to rest, your trunk and your striving alike; quiet at the center and not merely at the edges, you are without fault.",
"Keep your jaws still and let your words come ordered and few; speaking only what is measured, the regret you might have spoken into being never arises.",
"Stillness ripened into wholeness, calm that comes from the depths of you and not from holding the breath; this noble, settled quiet brings good fortune."
],
"53": [
"Like the wild goose nearing the shore, you take the first careful step into the unknown; the beginning feels exposed and tongues may wag, but go gently and there is no fault.",
"The goose reaches the safe rock, and there is food and quiet company to share; having found firm footing, enjoy it in peace, and good fortune is yours.",
"Advancing too far onto the bleak high ground, you push past your proper stage and strain everything; growth forced out of order goes wrong, so guard now against what would prey on you.",
"The goose alights in a tree and finds at last a flat branch to rest on; in a place not quite made for you, seek the bit of safe ground that will hold you, and you take no harm.",
"The goose nears the summit, and though for a long, barren while the union seems fruitless and misunderstood, hold on, for in the end nothing can keep the good from ripening.",
"The goose rises into the high cloud-ways, and even its dropped feathers are gathered for sacred use; grown fully and in order, your life becomes a blessing far beyond yourself."
],
"54": [
"You enter in a lesser place, like a younger bride who does not lead; yet even one who limps can still walk, so make good use of the modest role, and what you undertake from it prospers.",
"Seeing clearly with one eye, holding faithful where another has wandered; keep your own quiet loyalty even when little is given back, and that solitary constancy serves you well.",
"Grasping for a standing not offered, you sink to a meaner place than you began; reaching above your station here only lowers you, so wait rather than force the rise.",
"The maiden lets the season pass, holding out unmarried for the right match; better to wait past the expected hour than to settle wrongly, for the true union comes in its own good time.",
"Take the high place adorned more plainly than your attendants, beauty kept inward rather than displayed; modest where you could be grand, like the nearly full moon, you draw good fortune.",
"The basket is held up empty and the rite is gone through with no life in it, all form and no substance; an empty observance furthers nothing, so do not mistake the gesture for the thing."
],
"55": [
"You meet the one who matches you, your equal and complement; stay together through the rich first stretch without overstaying, and going forward you meet with welcome.",
"The light is so curtained that stars show at noon, and reaching out you meet only suspicion; do not force it, but reach the closed heart through steady sincerity, and good fortune comes.",
"The obscuring grows so thick that even the small stars appear at midday, and your strong right arm is broken, leaving you unable to act; when the time so disables you, do nothing rash, and no blame is yours.",
"Out of the deepest shadow, where stars show at noon, you meet at last the one of like spirit who can act with you; that meeting in the dark turns it toward good fortune.",
"Open yourself to the able and the wise, and let their gifts come to you; welcoming what is excellent, you draw blessing and renown, and good fortune with them.",
"Rich in your house yet walling yourself in, you screen off everyone until you peer out and see no one at all; pride that hoards its abundance alone ends in long, blind isolation and misfortune."
],
"56": [
"A stranger far from home who fusses over petty things and clings to trifles makes himself small and draws misfortune down; in a strange place, keep your dignity and your aim.",
"The traveler reaches a good inn, his belongings safe, and earns the loyalty of a faithful helper; modest and honest on the road, you find shelter and trustworthy company.",
"He meddles and offends until the inn burns and his helper deserts him; a stranger who throws his weight about loses the very goodwill that kept him safe, and stands in danger.",
"He finds a resting place and the means to get by, yet his heart stays uneasy, for it is not truly home; take the shelter and the security gratefully, but do not mistake it for belonging.",
"With one well-aimed shot he brings down the pheasant and wins both praise and a place; let a single fitting act show your worth, and even in a strange land it earns you honor.",
"Careless and high-spirited, he lets the nest burn, laughing before he understands, then weeps for what his heedlessness has cost; lose your footing through carelessness on the road and the loss is real."
],
"57": [
"Wavering back and forth, gentle to the point of having no spine; here you need the firm, single-minded resolve of a warrior to give your softness a direction.",
"Search out the hidden influence working under the surface, bringing in plenty of honest help to bring it to light; patient, thorough seeking like this brings good fortune and no blame.",
"Turning the same thing over and over, deliberating without end and never acting; gentleness that only hesitates and repeats itself sinks into humiliation.",
"Hold a clear aim and the regret dissolves; modest yet decisive, you gain on every side, as a good hunt brings in game of every kind.",
"Make the needed change carefully, weighing it well before and tending it well after; though the start was unpromising, see it through with steady resolve and it ends in good fortune.",
"You probe and yield so far that you lose your very means to act, your property and your ax both gone; gentleness pushed past all firmness undoes you, and clinging to it now brings misfortune."
],
"58": [
"Quiet, self-contained gladness that leans on nothing outside itself; needing no one to give it reasons, this contented joy brings good fortune.",
"Joy that springs from real sincerity within; open and honest in your gladness, you draw good fortune and the old regret melts away.",
"Chasing pleasure from outside, grasping after amusements to fill the hollow; gladness sought this way, from without rather than within, leads to misfortune.",
"Torn between a higher joy and a cheaper one, weighing the two, you find no peace; clear away the lesser temptation and the true gladness arrives.",
"Giving your trust openly to what is corrosive, to charming influences that wear you down; sincerity poured into what dissolves you is a real danger, so see them for what they are.",
"Joy that lures and flatters, given over wholly to being charmed; pleasure with nothing firm beneath it pulls you along by the nose, so let it not become your master."
],
"59": [
"At the first hardening, act promptly with all the strength you have, like a willing horse; clear the misunderstanding before it sets, and good fortune follows the early help.",
"When estrangement begins to chill you, hurry toward what steadies and supports you, lean into the warm and the firm; turn to your support in time and the regret dissolves.",
"Dissolve the hard knot of your own self-regard, set aside what you wanted for yourself; melt that small fixed center and there is nothing left to regret.",
"Break up even your own narrow faction for the sake of the larger whole; scattering the small clique gathers a greater unity, a turn the small-minded never imagine, and it brings the highest good fortune.",
"Send out one great rousing call that cuts through the confusion like sweat breaking a fever; give the scattered a true rallying center, and standing for it you remain without blame.",
"Disperse the danger before it can wound, keeping yourself and yours clear of the spreading harm; to withdraw to a safe distance from what would draw blood is no fault but wisdom."
],
"60": [
"Sometimes the time is closed, and staying within your own door and yard is exactly right; hold back when holding back is called for, and there is no fault.",
"But when the moment opens and you still hide behind your gate, holding back out of timidity, you miss the hour and it goes badly; know when restraint has become mere fear.",
"Set yourself no limits, spend without measure, and the lament that follows is your own doing; own that honestly, mend it, and the blame need not remain.",
"Accept your limits easily, settling into them without strain or resentment; restraint worn so lightly becomes a quiet, lasting success.",
"Limit yourself gently, beginning with your own conduct before you ask it of others; this sweet, self-imposed measure brings good fortune, and from it you go forward esteemed.",
"Limits driven to a harsh, bitter extreme cannot last and bring misfortune if you cling to them; ease the severity, and the regret you feel at loosening it is rightly let go."
],
"61": [
"Be inwardly ready and settled, and good fortune follows; but let a hidden, divided motive creep in and the unrest of it will give you no peace. Stay single-hearted.",
"A crane calls in the shade and its young answers from afar, heart reaching heart unseen; speak from your true depth and the kindred soul responds, glad to share the cup with you.",
"You hang your whole steadiness on another, so you swing with them, now drumming, now weeping, now still; a truth that leans entirely on someone else rises and falls at their mercy.",
"Like the moon almost full, turn away from your former companions to face the source of light alone; leaving the team to follow what is higher is no betrayal and no fault.",
"Hold a truth so real it binds others to you, a sincerity that links heart to heart and keeps the whole together; standing in that, you are without blame.",
"Empty words straining upward like a cock crowing to reach heaven, sound with no substance beneath it; clinging to mere show and noise, however persistently, only brings misfortune."
],
"62": [
"The small bird, restless, flies too high too soon and meets with disaster; in a time for staying low, straining upward beyond your reach brings only harm.",
"Reaching past the great one you cannot attain, you meet instead the modest helper within your reach, and that is enough; aim where you can actually arrive, and there is no fault.",
"Sure of yourself and dropping your guard in a careful time, you leave your back open to a blow; overlook the small precautions now and misfortune slips in behind you.",
"Meet the matter directly without overstepping, and you stay free of fault; pressing forward now is dangerous, so do not force it, stay on guard, and hold steadily to your course.",
"Dense clouds gather but no rain falls; the conditions are not yet ripe to give. Reach modestly for what is near and within grasp rather than waiting on the great release.",
"Overshooting the mark entirely, climbing past all measure like a bird that flies too far and is lost; excess in a time that begs for restraint brings misfortune and real injury."
],
"63": [
"Just past the finish, you rein in the wheels and only wet your tail at the ford; hold yourself back from rushing on, and that early restraint keeps you free of fault.",
"Something needed is lost and you are tempted to chase it; do not run after it, for grasping now is undignified, and in its own time it comes back to you.",
"Even a hard-won victory costs long, grinding years to secure; when the great effort is finally done, do not hand the keeping of it to the small and unworthy.",
"At the height, the finest garment is already fraying into rags; nothing completed stays perfect, so stay watchful the whole day through and tend the small decay before it spreads.",
"The grand sacrifice of the one who has arrived wins less true blessing than the small, sincere offering of the one still striving; a humble heart counts for more now than a lavish show.",
"Lingering proudly at the summit, you let your head sink under the water; cling to the completed thing past its hour and the very success becomes your danger."
],
"64": [
"Plunging ahead too eagerly at the very start, you soak your tail at the crossing; rush the beginning before you are ready and you earn only humiliation.",
"Hold yourself in check, braking your wheels rather than charging on; this patient restraint at the threshold, kept steady, brings good fortune.",
"On the brink but not yet ready, to strike out now would go wrong; gather your strength first, and then, when prepared, set out to cross the great water.",
"Put your whole resolve into the decisive effort and the regret falls away; sustained, wholehearted struggle against the obstacle wins through in the end and earns its lasting reward.",
"The hard work is bearing fruit and your light shines clear and true; hold faithfully to the end, and this clarity brings good fortune with no regret left in it.",
"Sharing wine in honest confidence as the goal comes near is no fault; but let the celebration tip into excess and lose your head, and you forfeit the very thing you had all but won."
]
};
